l";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}h2{padding-top:0pt;-webkit-text-decoration-skip:none;color:#ffffff;font-weight:700;text-decoration:underline;font-size:24pt;padding-bottom:0pt;line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;text-decoration-skip-ink:none;font-family:"Arial";orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}h3{padding-top:16pt;color:#434343;font-size:14pt;padding-bottom:4pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}h4{padding-top:14pt;color:#666666;font-size:12pt;padding-bottom:4pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}h5{padding-top:12pt;color:#666666;font-size:11pt;padding-bottom:4pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}h6{padding-top:12pt;color:#666666;font-size:11pt;padding-bottom:4pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;font-style:italic;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}</style></head><body class="c75"><div><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c28"></span></p></div><p class="c4"><span class="c3">This is the OOC/IC Handbook to refer to. Everything in here is law. You should read the entire handbook and </span><span class="c3">it&#39;s </span><span class="c1">recommended you memorize the highlighted areas/words. Things may be subject to change based on the server&rsquo;s choices. Thank you.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c20 c3 c15">Index:</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c3 c96">(Click on the blue word to bring you to the page.)</span><span class="c3"><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span class="c33 c15 c47"><a class="c39" href="#id.erutuptpkqfd">Social and Unit Conduct</a></span></p><ul class="c30 lst-kix_7hcw147e3j98-0 start"><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c3">CCA</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;Structure.</span></li><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c1">Black Marks.</span></li><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c1">Unit Etiquette.</span></li><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c1">Radio Etiquette.</span></li><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c1">Codewords.</span></li><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c1">Breaching.</span></li><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c1">Patrol behavior.</span></li></ul><p class="c4 c51"><span class="c33 c15 c47"><a class="c39" href="#id.v55ce3flq7ce">Ranks</a></span></p><ul class="c30 lst-kix_w0r6icdwurse-0 start"><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c1">Equipment.</span></li><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c1">Duties.</span></li><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c1">Divisions.</span></li></ul><p class="c4 c51"><span class="c33 c15 c47"><a class="c39" href="#id.va1fzer54tcx">Radio Codes</a></span></p><ul class="c30 lst-kix_k666038jmbuf-0 start"><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c1">10 digit series.</span></li></ul><p class="c4"><span class="c3">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><span class="c33 c15 c47"><a class="c39" href="#id.w903hb7scjyx">Loyalty Points/System</a></span></p><ul class="c30 lst-kix_34nmbwhg7usn-0 start"><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c1">Rewards and Tiers.</span></li><li class="c4 c36"><span class="c3">Distribution of points.</span></li></ul><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c45 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c45 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><a id="id.erutuptpkqfd"></a><p class="c4"><span class="c20 c3 c15">CODE OF CONDUCT</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c3 c15">Combine</span><span class="c3 c15">&nbsp;Civil Authority </span><span class="c1">officers are the muscle of the Universal Union. Providing security to the cities of Earth in a brutal yet orderly manner. Metropolice units remain anonymous, and are never to be seen without their faceplates in public view. The Combine Civil Authority maintains control not only through oppressive and violent tactics but also in generally peaceful cooperation with Union Loyalists.Those selected few who are lucky enough to become an officer receive perks of better food, housing, personal hygiene, and overall superior quality of life. A unit may do what they wish, as long as they maintain social stability, follow orders and continue being loyal to the Universal Union.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c71 c9 c3">Units will serve with this format as their identification.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c3">CCA.</span><span class="c3">CITY#-DIVISION.RANK.DIGITS(12345)[X][X]</span><span class="c33 c31 c87 c3 c95">&nbsp;(i.e. CCA.C08-UNION.i3.12345[X][X])</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c29 c15">City#</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;= Current city of service.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c29 c15">DIVISION</span><span class="c3 c15">&nbsp;</span><span class="c1">= The current Division system the officer belongs to. (i.e. Union, Helix, Grid, Judge.)</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c29 c15">DIGITS</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;= The unit&rsquo;s identification number, typically five digits. Numbers can range from 00000 to 99999.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c29 c15">[X]</span><span class="c29">&nbsp;</span><span class="c29 c15">Black Marks</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;= The unit&rsquo;s visible markings for identification of poor behavior. For a single black mark, it would look like this; [X]. For two; [X][X]. Once the unit hits three blackmarks, they are deserviced.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c15">Black Marks</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">The punishment system of the CCA, they are given when units have failed to complete a task or show poor behavior. (i.e.Failing to show respect to Command, ignoring an EpU&rsquo;s orders, etc.)</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Black marks may be issued by an EpU to their own members of their divisions, and by OfC and up to anyone below. To appeal, you must speak to the unit who applied them, or have a Captain remove them.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c15">Unit Etiquette</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c3 c31">Towards superiors:</span><span class="c3">&nbsp;Respect and professionalism should always be present when speaking to or being spoken to by a superior. Address them by sir or ma&rsquo;am, or by rank </span><span class="c33 c3">when inside the Nexus</span><span class="c1">. Friendly relationships with your officers are allowed. This distinct behavior towards superior officers however, should never be shown outside the nexus as it puts a target on the head of your superior officer as you may give their higher rank away to any possible malignancy in the area. </span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c3">Towards other units:</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;Positive relationships are encouraged in the CCA, as cohesion and camaraderie are improved in a workplace that requires us to rely on each other.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Friendly conversation and banter are allowed, permitted it is the appropriate audience.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Romantic relationships are allowed but must understand that the relationship is to not get in the way of their duties.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c31 c3">Towards citizens:</span><span class="c3">&nbsp;Your attitude towards citizens should be professional. Be quick to resolve citizen&rsquo;s issues or reports. Overcasual or vulgar language should not be used, but is acceptable in a situation where you need to either intimidate a citizen or win them over. While this may apply to regular citizens, </span><span class="c31 c3">do not assert an aggressive tone to loyalists</span><span class="c1">, as they have earned steps towards enlightenment.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c15 c32">Radio Etiquette</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c3">Units </span><span class="c3">are to never</span><span class="c3">&nbsp;say the radio frequency out loud, especially on the radio or any public area. Units should always make sure to view their objectives for the most current radio frequency. </span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c3 c15">Footnote:</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;Overwatch is the representative of the &ldquo;Pure Union&rdquo; faction (OTA, helicopters, etc.)</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Overwatch is the collective of the forces. Dispatcher is the voice you hear issue orders. Though Dispatcher&rsquo;s &ldquo;callsign&rdquo; is Overwatch, it&rsquo;s a generalized term.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c15">Breaching</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">The act of breaching is to enter a room in the most orderly fashion. To execute a breach, the following will be done. </span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Step 1: A unit of any rank will say &ldquo;Stack&rdquo; This signifies units they are preparing to breach the room. When this is said, units will line up on the wall parallel to the door.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Step 2: &ldquo;Lock.&rdquo; When Lock is heard, weapons are loaded and are ready to fire. It is during this period that the Breacher forces the door open in a way.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Step 3: &ldquo;Inject&rdquo; is the final command during a breach. This is when the units enter, in the form of Pointman, Breacher, and Rearguard.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">There are three positions for breaching, though it can be argued one unit may do two.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c3 c15 c33">Breache</span><span class="c33 c3">r</span><span class="c1">: The person responsible for breaking down the door and throwing the flash. This is typically the Command (EpU, i1. Etc.)</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c33 c3 c15">Pointman</span><span class="c1">: The first person into the room after the Breacher has tossed the flash. Typically a ranked number unit. (i5-i1.)</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c33 c3 c15">Rearguard</span><span class="c1">: The person who covers the pointman from any immediate harm, such as targets missed, etc. This is controlled by anyone.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c6 c66"></span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c6 c66"></span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c6 c66"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c15">Patrol Behavior</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c3">Patrols are essential to maintaining a solid presence in the city streets. Patrols should be led by the highest ranking unit on the patrol. In the case of equal ranking units should </span><span class="c31 c3">quickly pick who is the Command.</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;Units are required to form a patrol and move around the city if they are not otherwise occupied with official duty. Patrols are typically two to three units. Any more units is considered a &ldquo;Squad.&rdquo; Squads may be utilized on operations that require more security, or breaching any rebel-active areas.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Normal patrol duties may include answering citizen questions, watching for suspicious behavior, checking in on businesses, etc. </span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c3">When dealing with reports, units should radio in before responding.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c70 c31 c3"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c3">Use of callsigns: Units may use temporary callsigns for their name of the patrol.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c31 c3 c70"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c15">Union Wash</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Union washing is the function of one being exposed to Universal Union messaging, and becoming more loyal on a psychological level. When one is Union-washed, they typically retain their former personalities, but have a more keen sense to serve the Union.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Two forms of Union-wash;</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c33 c3 c15 c58"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c33 c3 c15">Mild Union Wash</span><span class="c1">: Received at the rank of i3, i1, and EpU. MUW is common, and it generally can be administered by an i3 Helix. It may even be applied to loyalists depending on the case.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c33 c3 c15">Heavy Union Wash</span><span class="c1">: Received at the rank of UNIFORM EpU, any OfC, CmD and up. There may be specific instances for HUW to be applied, and should be applied by the approval of an OfC.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Union washing can &ldquo;stack up&rdquo; on effects. Mild Union washing is useful to enforce positive ideology, less intrusive and easier to perform. Heavy Union-washing is more insurance, as two sessions may guarantee almost nigh possibility of defecting, but defects any personality.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c15">Memory-Replacement</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c3">Memory replacement, or </span><span class="c3 c15">MR</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;for short is the function when certain memories or pivotal moments in history are either erased or distorted from an individual&#39;s mind. MR is not commonly used as overuse can cause destabilization of one&rsquo;s mind, however it&rsquo;s a requirement at higher ranks to progress. </span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">MR can also change an individual&#39;s personality, as MR can be used to affect key elements in one&rsquo;s psych.</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">When MR is used, it is for the following;</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Overwatch Soldier Transition. (Very heavily)</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Promotion to DvL and up. (Light to moderate)</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Removing certain ideas, or thoughts from an HVT or VIP. (Light)</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Typically, one will attempt to use Union-Washing over Memory-Replacement first, unless explicitly told otherwise.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c15">Commanding Officer Behavior</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">Majority of the time, the Metropolice Command Officers will be spending time inside the Nexus, unless it&rsquo;s a matter that needs explicit attention. Standard duties are to train units, introduce units into their divisions and provide orders and authorizations. They will spend time monitoring their unit&rsquo;s behaviors and watching units for promotion. Command officers will issue orders to their subordinates and see to it that the city is running ideally.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c32 c15">Field Marshals</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c3">Field Marshals are those who stand as the absolute commander on the field. They are any unit who is dictated as the field representative of the Commander. Their word is law on the field, and is followed to the letter. Field Marshals are uncommon, and are appointed when necessary to maintain order. Field Marshals have absolute authority, and cannot be undermined by anyone except the City Commander and High Command. They may be in power for as long as the City Commander has placed them, or for a specified duration, or operation. On the off chance that the Field Marshal is abusing their given power, two out of three captains must speak to counteract it. Being placed as a Field Marshal is one of the highest honors, and is shown as trust placed into an individual unit&rsquo;s hands. That said, failures as a Field Marshal will have massive consequences. </span><span class="c31 c3">To qualify for Field Marshal, a unit must proceed through a heavy Union-Wash and light memory replacement.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c8 c66">Quartermasters</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c1">The armory operators of the CCA. A unit is stripped of their division and rank upon selection to become a QrM. QrMs have the ability to give supplies and firearms to a unit, however they may deny a unit supplies if they see fit, unless the unit requesting is a DvL or above. QrMs are allowed to request a supply resupply if needed. QrMs, as well as being the Armory Operator, also carry the responsibilities of making sure CCA is sufficiently happy with their living conditions, as well as making sure rations are in good supply.</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c8 c66"></span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c20 c3 c15">Divisions</span></p><p class="c4"><span class="c3">In the Combine Civil Authority, there&rsquo;s numerous ways </span><span class="c3">of running</span><span class="c1">&nbsp;the city. They&rsquo;re all adjusted for the environment around them. In the current setting there are these;</span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><a id="t.4cb739904286c3e78c249988d3aa47696f9a2b66"></a><a id="t.0"></a><table class="c10"><tbody><tr class="c34"><td class="c13" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c25"><span class="c71 c9 c3">Division Name</span></p></td><td class="c21" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c25"><span class="c6 c3">Specialized duties</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c77"><td class="c13" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c25"><span class="c48 c3 c15">UNION</span></p><p class="c25 c5"><span class="c48 c3 c87"></span></p></td><td class="c21" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c12"><span class="c1">Field units. They are the bulk of the Combine Civil Authority that exemplify field tactics and order. Their lack of specialization is what makes them optimal for ground control, pursuing Union leads to leadership, CQC and tactics training.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c94"><td class="c13" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c25"><span class="c3 c15 c48">HELIX</span></p><p class="c25 c5"><span class="c48 c87 c3"></span></p></td><td class="c21" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c12"><span class="c1">To put simply, Medics. They are in charge of field medical assistance and prescribing medications. They are able bodied units that can perform surgical operations to medication prescriptions. They are the first unit to come to if in illness.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c93"><td class="c13" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c25"><span class="c48 c3 c15">GRID</span></p><p class="c25 c5"><span class="c48 c87 c3"></span></p></td><td class="c21" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c12"><span class="c1">Mechanics of the Union. They are tasked with fielding electronic equipment such as turrets, scanners, bio-gates, cameras, mines and any wired function.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c17"><td class="c13" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c25"><span class="c48 c3 c15">JUDGE</span></p><p class="c25 c5"><span class="c48 c3 c15"></span></p></td><td class="c21" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c12"><span class="c1">Units responsible for being Jail Wardens, handling interrogations and executions, and handling investigations of higher scale.</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c4 c5"><span class="c1"></span></p><p cla